{"id": "food_FOOD00203", "name": "Muscadine grape (food medium)", "category": "food", "organism_scope": "food microbiome / general", "aerobic": true, "description": "Food-derived medium: metabolizable components of Muscadine grape (Vitis rotundifolia) [Fruits] from FooDB, plus a standard M9 mineral base. Organic components use presence-based uptake bounds; FooDB content retained. Measured compounds with no BiGG exchange are listed under uncovered.", "namespace": "bigg", "provenance": {"source_type": "database", "citation": "FooDB v2020-04-07 (Wishart DS et al., foodb.ca). Content sources: PHENOL EXPLORER, USDA.", "doi": "", "url": "https://foodb.ca/downloads", "notes": "Organic components mapped from FooDB compounds to BiGG via InChIKey/name. Mineral base added. Bounds presence-based; foodb_content retained. Unmapped measured compounds kept in uncovered (v2 completeness fix). IMPORTANT: composition values are taken from the archived FooDB 2020-04-07 CSV data release; FooDB's live food page no longer displays this bulk composition, so it will appear empty. Verify individual compounds via the per-component cross-reference links. Underlying content was aggregated by FooDB from USDA / DTU / Phenol Explorer.", "data_release": "FooDB 2020-04-07 CSV release (foodb.ca/downloads)", "food_record": "https://foodb.ca/foods/FOOD00203", "verification": "expert-curated (multi-source food composition; growth-relevant profile completed, FooDB noise removed)", "curation_date": "2026-07-17", "curation_sources": ["USDA FoodData Central FDC 173040 (Grapes, muscadine, raw) - full whole-berry nutrient panel", "FooDB FOOD00203", "Ector et al., Optimum quality parameters of muscadine grape juices/beverages (sugar & acid means: fructose 5.51%, glucose 5.16%, sucrose 1.89%; malate 0.50%, tartrate 0.26%)", "Sandhu & Gu, Fruit Quality/Nutraceutical properties of 58 muscadine varieties (Vitis rotundifolia)", "Antioxidants 2021, 10(6):914, doi:10.3390/antiox10060914 (organic-acid profile; malate+tartrate ~90% at ripeness)", "Foods 2021, 10(5):1101, doi:10.3390/foods10051101 (juice tartaric 2.6-4.8 g/L)", "Lamikanra O. 1997, free amino acids of Noble muscadine, PMID 10606539"], "curation_notes": "Dominant carbon/energy sources are D-glucose and D-fructose (~3.7-3.9 g/100g each) plus the previously-missing organic acids malic (~0.50 g/100g) and tartaric (~0.26 g/100g); sucrose is minor. Muscadine is distinctively high in manganese, dietary fiber, and skin phenolics (ellagic acid, resveratrol). Retinol was removed as an implausible animal vitamer (carotenoids substituted); the USDA riboflavin figure (1.5 mg) is a known implausible outlier and was down-corrected to the grape-family referenc", "curation_added": ["malic acid (dominant organic acid, ~0.50 g/100g)", "tartaric acid (~0.26 g/100g)", "citric acid (trace)", "quantitative individual sugar amounts (glucose 3.67, fructose 3.92, sucrose 0.57 g/100g)", "total protein + free amino acid profile (alanine/histidine/arginine)", "quantitative minerals (K, Ca, Mg, P, Na, Fe, Zn, Cu, Mn)", "vitamin C, riboflavin, folate amounts", "dietary fiber, total fat, water", "lutein+zeaxanthin"], "curation_removed": [{"name": "Retinol", "reason": "Preformed retinol is an animal-derived vitamer; plants/grapes contain provitamin-A carotenoids (beta-carotene) not retinol. FooDB artifact; vitamin-A activity is captured by the carotenoids instead."}, {"name": "CO2 CO2", "reason": "Metabolic-model exchange/gas species, not a food-composition nutrient."}, {"name": "O2 O2", "reason": "Metabolic-model exchange/gas species, not a food nutrient."}, {"name": "H+", "reason": "Proton/pH model artifact, not a quantifiable food nutrient."}, {"name": "Fe2+ mitochondria", "reason": "Model compartment-tagged duplicate of iron; consolidated into a single 'iron' entry."}, {"name": "Iron (Fe3+)", "reason": "Redox/species-tagged duplicate of iron; consolidated into a single 'iron' entry."}, {"name": "Co2+", "reason": "Cobalt: not measured in the US